<paragraph id="63858DD2C49DC46B9290C41D5E197073" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="21AFA33F4C35EB6E69DD1FEBE94C0CED" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
TENERIFE: 
<normalizedToken id="9B5F10193AE0D369A564D95A11BCB568" originalValue="Guía">Guia</normalizedToken>
de Isora, Playa de San Juan, SE of the village, shallow, dry barranco, a single shrub, relic of former plantation (?), 14.01.2019, 
<emphasis id="3CA0A019808189A5A4A0C2D6C21B1297" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">F. Verloove</emphasis>
13438 (BR); Santa Cruz de Tenerife, San 
<normalizedToken id="E37EF4E97F8971C752690755AADDF00A" originalValue="Andrés">Andres</normalizedToken>
, Barranco de San 
<normalizedToken id="59A5C741A0890CC4AB41F810B09BBE0A" originalValue="Andrés">Andres</normalizedToken>
, dry gravelly riverbed, two young shrubs, self-sown, 22.12.2019, 
<emphasis id="7746BD1B699A9DE225C67FCAA0DF9CD4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">F. Verloove</emphasis>
13738 (BR).https://observation.org/observation/205285935/; https://observation.org/observation/205286074/
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="68F056CCB0F9F132622297D088425A3C" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph id="2A17EC3EF66AAEFFA53E6E595C6210D7" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CA1C20D4077FB5C159E8AB44CFE0878C" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName id="6D120281C9AF8B9CE37AFF099BBD0B57" authorityName="N. E. Br. ex Britton &amp; P. Wilson" authorityYear="1925" baseAuthorityName="Mill." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Lippia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lippia alba" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis id="BBFAF08E991689FB2A2B3F3574E9589E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Lippia alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to southern Texas (U.S.A.), Mexico, the Caribbean, Central America and South America. It is widely cultivated as an ornamental or for its aromatic foliage. In places where it was formerly introduced, it relatively easily naturalises, for instance, in Australia (
<bibRefCitation id="61811803929D9ED564A3EF2C0F5FCFC6" author="Munir, AA" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Adelaide Botanic Gardens" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="129 - 145" refId="B6509370" refString="Munir, AA, 1993. A taxonomic revision of the genus Lippia [Houst. ex] Linn. (Verbenacae) in Australia. Journal of the Adelaide Botanic Gardens 15 (2): 129 - 145" title="A taxonomic revision of the genus Lippia [Houst. ex] Linn. (Verbenacae) in Australia" volume="15" year="1993">Munir 1993</bibRefCitation>
). In Europe, it was recently reported for the first time from a single locality in Portugal (
<bibRefCitation id="09A5F4865A889E9AC1D82F45BBAD443B" author="Verloove, F" journalOrPublisher="Folia Botanica Extremadurensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="5 - 23" refId="B6510000" refString="Verloove, F, Alves, P, 2016. New vascular plant records for the western part of the Iberian Peninsula (Portugal and Spain). Folia Botanica Extremadurensis 10: 5 - 23" title="New vascular plant records for the western part of the Iberian Peninsula (Portugal and Spain)" volume="10" year="2016">Verloove and Alves 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA50227FE16F872752FF3B3B04A3C8A2" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In 2019, this species was recorded in two localities in Tenerife. In Playa de San Juan, a single shrub grows in a very shallow, dried-out ravine. It may be a mere relic of former cultivation there. In a second locality, in San 
<normalizedToken id="CD9FB6D2137C2E7C8FAF11F5CC9140BF" originalValue="Andrés">Andres</normalizedToken>
, however, two young, obviously self-sown shrubs were found growing on the gravel of the dry riverbed (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2882EA740A64583C7D293FA94659BB86" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6510155" captionText="Figure 6. Lippia alba, Santa Cruz de Tenerife (San Andres), December 2019." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e62878.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/494347" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
